5_6	0.14613232	Yet antitrust experts say that the Norris testimony was not a knockout punch on its own and that its legal power may hinge on earlier testimony, in closed sessions, on the prices Microsoft charges PC makers for its Windows operating system.
5_7	0.10139143	Big, powerful and itself long a target of government antitrust suits, IBM was an imperfect object of sympathy as the representative witness for PC makers.
5_8	0.13577016	Ever since IBM selected Microsoft to supply the operating system for the first IBM PC in 1981, IBM has been out-hustled and outsmarted by Microsoft in the PC business _ not the sort of behavior the nation's antitrust laws were meant to prohibit.
5_9	0.13183264	The government, of course, had recognized that IBM's size, reach and complicated history with Microsoft could be used by Microsoft's lawyers to try to undercut its contentions.
5_10	0.10975409	For months, the Justice Department had urged other major computer makers to take the stand _ and it pushed particularly hard for Ted Waitt, the chairman of Gateway Inc.
5_11	0.067921279	, who ultimately decided against it.
5_12	0.10011988	Microsoft's defense, antitrust experts say, may be that IBM was told it would pay a higher price for Windows unless it agreed to ``reduce, drop or eliminate'' shipments of OS/2, IBM's competing operating system.
5_13	0.078259683	On its face, such an invitation to a competitor to reduce competition would be an antitrust violation, even if the offer were rejected.
5_14	0.10217455	But the legal standard in such cases, established in a 1984 ruling involving American Airlines, is that the evidence be ``uniquely unequivocal'' _ in the airline case, the evidence was a tape-recorded offer to jointly raise fares.
5_15	0.064230764	With Microsoft, there is no such clear-cut evidence.
5_16	0.089883307	The contract proposals presented in court were a series of suggested discounts on the price of Windows if IBM agreed to certain promotion and marketing efforts on behalf of Windows.
5_17	0.09700467	No Microsoft contract offer, Norris conceded, stated specifically that IBM must ``drop or eliminate'' OS/2.
5_18	0.13409585	But he insisted that the overall effect of the Microsoft terms would be to ``kill OS/2 in the markeplace''.
5_19	0.11883426	Still, antitrust experts note, it is certainly legal for Microsoft to offer a distributor _ as the IBM PC business was _ incentives to aggressively distribute its product.
5_20	0.093673618	If accepting those incentives means featuring Microsoft's Windows over OS/2 _ made by another unit of IBM _ that is mainly a business decision for IBM to make, they say.
5_21	0.18002518	IBM turned down the Microsoft proposal.
5_22	0.1315822	A shrewdly devised offer by Microsoft perhaps, but antitrust experts say it was probably not a violation.
